ChatGPT:
   
In your program, when std::exit(0) is called in the b() function, it terminates the program immediately. 
This prevents the destructor of myApple from being called, as the program doesn't perform 
normal stack unwinding and object destruction.

However, Valgrind doesn't report a memory leak in this case 
because the memory allocated for the Apple object is not dynamically allocated 
(it's on the stack, not the heap). 
Valgrind typically reports memory leaks for heap-allocated memory that is not freed properly, 
but in this case, the stack memory is automatically reclaimed by the operating system when the program exits.

So, even though the destructor is not called, the stack memory used by myApple is cleaned up by the OS, 
and thus Valgrind does not report it as a leak.

